<paragraph blockId="3.[192,1442,1691,1927]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,360,1691,1717]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Identification.</emphasis>
Head, pronotum, and other parts of body are dark and marked with black, pale olive-yellow, and red; the red and black pattern of hind wings closely resembles red-winged species of 
<emphasis box="[1161,1295,1726,1752]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1870" box="[1161,1291,1726,1752]" class="Insecta" family="Romaleidae" genus="Chromacris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Chromacris</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
however the head and thorax are much more robust; tegmina can be shorter, as long as or longer than the hind femur; hind tibiae are usually red (
<bibRefCitation author="Roberts HR &amp; Carbonell CS" box="[445,771,1796,1822]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" pagination="43 - 58" refId="ref6054" refString="Roberts HR, Carbonell CS. 1982. A revision of the grasshopper genera Chromacris and Xestotrachelus (Orthoptera, Romaleidae, Romaleinae). Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences 43 (4): 43 - 58." type="journal article" year="1982">Roberts and Carbonell 1982</bibRefCitation>
); abdomen has red punctuations on the dorsal, lateral, and ventral regions, hind femora and tibiae possess no bands (
<figureCitation box="[863,960,1830,1857]" captionStart-0="Figure 1" captionStart-1="Figure 2" captionStartId-0="4.[191,267,1833,1859]" captionStartId-1="5.[192,270,1866,1892]" captionTargetBox-0="[210,1421,213,1803]" captionTargetBox-1="[196,1435,214,1836]" captionTargetId-0="figure-16@4.[210,1421,213,1803]" captionTargetId-1="figure-12@5.[196,1436,213,1836]" captionTargetPageId-0="4" captionTargetPageId-1="5" captionText-0="Figure 1. Live Xestotrachelus robustus (Bruner, 1911) specimens collected at Panga Ecological Reserve. A) Males trying to copulate with the female (bigger one). B) Female dorsal view. C) Female abdomen with red punctuations in the dorsal, lateral, and ventral regions." captionText-1="Figure 2. Pinned specimens of Xestotrachelus robustus (Bruner, 1911) collected at Panga Ecological Reserve. A) Female. B) Male. Scale bar = 0.5 cm." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5113776" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5113778" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5113776/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5113778/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Fig. 1–2</figureCitation>
). Phallic structures are similar to those in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walker" authorityYear="1870" box="[192,320,1865,1891]" class="Insecta" family="Romaleidae" genus="Chromacris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[192,320,1865,1891]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="2">Chromacris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differing by the aedeagal valves being strongly sclerotized and larger; rami of cingulum narrow and epiphallus with ancorae well developed (
<bibRefCitation author="Roberts HR &amp; Carbonell CS" box="[692,1012,1900,1926]" pageId="3" pageNumber="2" pagination="43 - 58" refId="ref6054" refString="Roberts HR, Carbonell CS. 1982. A revision of the grasshopper genera Chromacris and Xestotrachelus (Orthoptera, Romaleidae, Romaleinae). Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences 43 (4): 43 - 58." type="journal article" year="1982">Roberts and Carbonell 1982</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
