<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="5" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[192,1441,214,308]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,303,214,240]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">Remarks.</emphasis>
The tribe 
<taxonomicName box="[420,536,214,240]" class="Insecta" family="Romaleidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Romaleini">Romaleini</taxonomicName>
is characterized by grasshoppers marked by large size and color polymorphism. There are some details about 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bruner" authorityYear="1913" box="[524,681,248,274]" class="Insecta" family="Romaleidae" genus="Xestotrachelus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[524,681,248,274]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">Xestotrachelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that allow their distinction from the other 
<taxonomicName box="[1170,1286,248,274]" class="Insecta" family="Romaleidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Romaleini">Romaleini</taxonomicName>
grasshoppers found in South America:
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
